contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:18.880 --> 00:20.917
<i>We interrupt our
regularly scheduled programming</i>

00:21.040 --> 00:23.475
<i>to bring you the following
report from NBC News.</i>

00:23.800 --> 00:25.280
<i>Here now is Tom Brokaw.</i>

00:26.280 --> 00:28.670
<i>Good evening
from Des Moines, Iowa, tonight.</i>

00:28.760 --> 00:32.070
<i>The Democratic caucuses in the
state of Iowa now are underway,</i>

00:32.159 --> 00:34.470
<i>and the first results
have just been reported.</i>

00:35.040 --> 00:36.633
<i>The NBC News projection</i>

00:36.720 --> 00:39.474
<i>is that Walter Mondale
will be the winner.</i>

00:39.960 --> 00:42.077
<i>About half of those
attending the caucuses tonight</i>

00:42.160 --> 00:44.277
<i>who expressed a preference
for a candidate</i>

00:44.360 --> 00:45.714
<i>are for Mondale.</i>

00:46.080 --> 00:48.675
<i>All the other candidates are far behind.</i>

00:48.760 --> 00:51.992
<i>It does appear, however,
that Senator John Glenn</i>

00:52.080 --> 00:53.594
<i>will not finish second.</i>

00:54.040 --> 00:56.396
<i>And it appears that there's
a very good chance tonight</i>

00:56.480 --> 00:59.314
<i>that Gary Hart will be second
in the preferences</i>

00:59.400 --> 01:02.518
<i>of those attending
the Iowa caucuses tonight.</i>

01:02.600 --> 01:03.670
<i>Let some of the other...</i>

01:14.800 --> 01:15.950
His hair looks like shit.

01:16.040 --> 01:18.509
- When is he getting it cut?
- That is the new cut.

01:18.640 --> 01:20.199
We can't get a clear line.

01:20.280 --> 01:22.670
What? Are we at full stick?

01:23.560 --> 01:26.439
Jesus. Did you have to park
so close to the building?

01:27.680 --> 01:28.830
Okay, go, Steve!

01:29.320 --> 01:31.039
Yes, we learned just a few minutes ago

01:31.120 --> 01:33.715
that Senator Hart
will soon leave this hotel,

01:33.800 --> 01:36.952
head back to the convention hall,
where he will concede.

01:37.120 --> 01:40.670
Yes, he will concede to former
vice president Walter Mondale.

01:41.320 --> 01:43.200
Hart went into the primaries
a relative unknown,

01:45.760 --> 01:46.856
eclipsed by challengers
like John Glenn...

01:46.880 --> 01:48.473
I'm on my hands and knees,

01:49.440 --> 01:51.875
fiddling with these wires
behind the accelerator.

01:52.360 --> 01:53.430
I'm trying to get a...

01:56.160 --> 01:57.230
Congratulations.

01:58.760 --> 02:00.656
I'm fooling with the wires
behind the accelerator

02:00.680 --> 02:02.136
trying to jump-start
the damn thing, but...

02:02.160 --> 02:04.720
- You know how to do that?
- Well, golf carts are easy

02:04.800 --> 02:06.096
to jump-start, you got to get
the right wires together.

02:06.120 --> 02:08.430
Say he's been making phone calls
and thanking supporters

02:08.520 --> 02:12.150
and asking them to back
Walter Mondale's campaign.

02:12.560 --> 02:13.976
Okay, let's try another one. In three...

02:14.000 --> 02:15.760
Hey, asshole,
you're walking through my shot!

02:15.800 --> 02:17.473
- Yeah, sorry. Sorry.
- Come on!

02:17.560 --> 02:19.711
Hart won every state
west of the Mississippi

02:19.800 --> 02:21.917
in his fight
for the Democratic nomination,

02:22.000 --> 02:23.354
but in the end,

02:23.440 --> 02:27.559
it was a question taken
from a Wendy's advertisement

02:27.640 --> 02:30.360
that dogged his insurgent campaign.

02:30.440 --> 02:31.590
Roll tape. Go.

02:33.480 --> 02:35.176
<i>When... When I hear...
When I... When I hear...</i>

02:35.200 --> 02:36.616
<i>There are some specific ways to do that.</i>

02:36.640 --> 02:38.199
<i>When I hear your new ideas,</i>

02:38.280 --> 02:41.000
<i>I'm reminded of that ad,
"Where's the beef?"</i>

02:41.080 --> 02:42.480
<i>- Yeah?</i>
- Okay, go, Steve.

02:43.000 --> 02:44.150
Hart will take to the stage

02:44.240 --> 02:45.616
- later this evening...
- Wait. Hold it, Steve. Hold it.

02:45.640 --> 02:47.296
- To share his thoughts...
- We lost the signal.

02:47.320 --> 02:48.640
Are we facing south?

02:48.720 --> 02:50.656
- I think we're facing south.
- Steve, would you shut up?

02:50.680 --> 02:52.080
We lost the signal again.

02:52.760 --> 02:54.911
Well, maybe you should invest
in a goddamn compass.

02:55.000 --> 02:56.336
Would someone tell... Steve, shut up!

02:56.360 --> 02:57.920
When he took the New Hampshire primary.

02:58.600 --> 03:01.176
- Okay, no one's listening to me.
- At that point, it was anyone's game.

03:01.200 --> 03:04.318
This news tonight
resets the playing field.

03:04.400 --> 03:07.313
Insiders of both camps
say the challenge now,

03:07.400 --> 03:10.279
heading into the fall campaign,
will be to unify

03:10.360 --> 03:12.511
this very divided Democratic Party.

03:12.600 --> 03:14.671
The long fight
between Mondale and Hart...

03:23.800 --> 03:25.120
What's the plan for after?

03:25.200 --> 03:27.271
The body's still warm.
You want to talk about '88?

03:27.360 --> 03:29.556
- I mean drinks.
- That Hawaiian place.

03:29.640 --> 03:30.835
Polynesian.

03:32.520 --> 03:33.656
I don't know what he was talking about,

03:33.680 --> 03:35.637
but he was in that...
Carter's White House...

03:36.040 --> 03:38.794
- So, can you use it?
- I lost all feeling above the knuckle.

03:38.880 --> 03:40.712
I could always tell
when it's about to rain.

03:40.800 --> 03:42.519
- No, really?
- Yeah.

03:47.320 --> 03:48.470
Yeah, okay.

03:49.480 --> 03:50.550
I appreciate it, Walter.

03:54.200 --> 03:55.793
I'll come with you back to Denver.

03:55.920 --> 03:57.149
You should stay.

03:57.240 --> 03:58.356
Senator, it's time.

03:58.440 --> 04:00.033
Remember to hit homelessness, sir.

04:00.120 --> 04:02.157
- I don't want you to fly alone.
- I'll be fine.

04:02.240 --> 04:04.994
I'll take the kids.
You need to be in D.C.

04:05.080 --> 04:07.800
- I don't need to be anywhere.
- Yeah, you do.

04:07.880 --> 04:09.678
Senator, we need to roll.

04:17.760 --> 04:19.399
Are you really gonna
follow Mondale around

04:19.440 --> 04:22.035
- for another six months?
- My apartment is grim.

04:22.120 --> 04:24.776
- I'll take the free meals, though.
- Maybe they'd like your job, Quinn.

04:24.800 --> 04:27.360
It's a good plan.
Well, it was a good plan.

04:27.440 --> 04:29.591
They light the damn thing
on fire, don't they?

04:30.960 --> 04:32.560
There's no weapons allowed at the table.

04:32.600 --> 04:34.796
The only shot I want's whiskey.

04:34.920 --> 04:37.958
- To the wisdom of the framers.
- Jefferson and his slaves.

04:38.040 --> 04:39.190
Leave Jefferson out of it.

04:41.440 --> 04:43.557
- Gentlemen.
- Hey, Bob.

04:47.920 --> 04:49.816
Of course, they don't even
have a straw big enough

04:49.840 --> 04:52.071
- to reach down the bottom...
- You want a real drink?

04:52.160 --> 04:54.470
- You want a real drink?
- No, that is a real drink.

04:56.720 --> 04:59.030
<i>America is the land</i>

04:59.120 --> 05:03.000
<i>where dreams can come true
for all of us.</i>

05:08.680 --> 05:10.797
<i>Ladies and gentlemen
of the convention...</i>

05:11.400 --> 05:12.480
Thinking of going swimming?

05:12.560 --> 05:14.711
<i>My name is Geraldine Ferraro.</i>

05:18.360 --> 05:20.397
Remember our first trip
to New Hampshire?

05:21.200 --> 05:23.032
Come home in a Carter motorcade?

05:23.880 --> 05:26.440
And those two vans, you know,
that time we won the primary.

05:26.520 --> 05:28.318
Think Mondale's got a chance?

05:28.400 --> 05:30.357
Mondale? No. Reagan's gonna crush him.

05:31.400 --> 05:33.256
In four years, they won't
have an answer for us,

05:33.280 --> 05:35.317
- for our ideas.
- George Bush might.

05:37.280 --> 05:39.749
You think young people
are gonna vote for George Bush?

05:40.760 --> 05:42.399
If the economy keeps up.

05:47.600 --> 05:50.593
The world changes when young
people give a damn, Billy.

05:52.680 --> 05:54.416
We're the only ones
who'll give a damn about them.

05:54.440 --> 05:55.715
We should have won.

05:57.400 --> 05:58.993
That's not what this was about.

06:00.800 --> 06:01.995
Then what was it about?

06:04.040 --> 06:05.360
Now they know who we are.

06:16.080 --> 06:18.197
<i>- The circus.
- Jim, I would like to say,</i>

06:18.280 --> 06:20.749
<i>we do miss home,
and four months ago, we left,</i>

06:20.840 --> 06:22.399
<i>and I have not walked into my house,</i>

06:22.480 --> 06:25.040
<i>have not seen my puppies and my kittens
and all those things</i>

06:25.120 --> 06:27.077
<i>and our dear friends
that we love so much since.</i>

06:27.160 --> 06:29.117
<i>And so, to the people at home,
we love you,</i>

06:29.240 --> 06:30.720
<i>- we miss you and...
- Yes.</i>

06:31.080 --> 06:34.517
<i>And we hope all of the people
we love so much will forgive us.</i>

07:00.480 --> 07:02.136
- Give the president a little credit.
- No...

07:02.160 --> 07:03.992
One could argue
he's trying to keep us safe.

07:04.080 --> 07:06.390
No, President Reagan has
allowed our cities to decay,

07:06.480 --> 07:07.640
while he buys enough warheads

07:07.720 --> 07:09.598
to destroy this planet 30 times over.

07:10.400 --> 07:13.120
I mean, imagine if every school
could have a computer,

07:13.200 --> 07:14.656
every library, every home. That is...

07:14.680 --> 07:16.911
Well, why don't we just
buy everyone a microwave?

07:17.640 --> 07:19.279
And a television set, while we're at it.

07:19.360 --> 07:22.478
I'm interested in educating the next
generation, not entertaining them.

07:22.560 --> 07:24.870
You know, gentlemen,
this is beginning to sound

07:24.960 --> 07:26.394
something like a campaign debate.

07:26.480 --> 07:27.840
Mr. Billy Shore, what's the story?

07:27.920 --> 07:29.296
Do either of you
have anything to announce?

07:29.320 --> 07:30.456
It's not gonna happen today, Alan, okay?

07:30.480 --> 07:32.517
- After you, Senator.
- But keep asking.

07:32.600 --> 07:34.717
You and your younger
Democratic colleagues

07:34.800 --> 07:36.632
have been called the "Atari Democrats."

07:36.720 --> 07:38.313
I've heard. I didn't coin that.

07:38.400 --> 07:40.471
- Have you ever played Atari?
- Yes,

07:40.600 --> 07:42.910
I've tried <i>Asteroids</i>
a few times with my son.

07:43.680 --> 07:45.990
I mostly drifted around
getting pelted with rocks.

07:46.640 --> 07:48.438
Felt like my first term in the Senate.

07:49.440 --> 07:50.999
Did you see what Bono announced?

07:51.080 --> 07:52.753
He's running for mayor of Palm Springs.

07:52.840 --> 07:54.752
Oh, come on.

07:55.520 --> 07:57.591
I can certainly guess
his campaign slogan.

07:57.680 --> 07:59.478
"He's got you, babe."

07:59.560 --> 08:01.199
- He looks good.
- Yeah.

08:01.280 --> 08:02.656
- I've read your spy novel.
- Well, thank you.

08:02.680 --> 08:04.696
Hey, you guys be careful.
Let's put that inside right here.

08:04.720 --> 08:06.951
Now, these other candidates
are all decent guys.

08:07.040 --> 08:08.793
They all want what's best
for this country.

08:08.880 --> 08:09.996
But they're not gonna win.

08:10.080 --> 08:14.199
You know it, they know it.
More importantly, George Bush knows it.

08:14.280 --> 08:16.511
That's why they're all gunning for us.

08:17.440 --> 08:19.750
We lose this primary, that's it,

08:19.840 --> 08:21.718
we can kiss the White House good-bye.

08:21.880 --> 08:23.872
And kiss your future good-bye,
because...

08:23.960 --> 08:26.236
Will somebody pay the pizza guy?

08:28.160 --> 08:30.072
- How much is it?
- $17.99.

08:30.160 --> 08:32.720
If line three rings, don't pick up.
That's the fax.

08:32.799 --> 08:34.472
What if line one and two
are busy, though?

08:34.559 --> 08:35.960
Use line four.

08:36.039 --> 08:37.394
It's amazing.

08:37.679 --> 08:40.035
<i>We have a rusting industrial base.</i>

08:40.120 --> 08:41.634
How does he look that good?

08:41.720 --> 08:42.995
Genetics.

08:43.080 --> 08:44.992
Whose? Don Johnson's?

08:45.080 --> 08:46.799
Yeah. That's why I look like this.

08:46.920 --> 08:48.479
What if line four is busy?

08:48.840 --> 08:51.150
- Who the fuck did this?
- So, when you're exhausted

08:51.240 --> 08:53.232
and your feet hurt
and your fingers are frozen

08:53.320 --> 08:56.313
from knocking on doors in Nashua
for 12 hours straight,

08:56.760 --> 08:59.355
you miss your boyfriend,
your girlfriend, your

08:59.440 --> 09:00.590
kids...

09:02.400 --> 09:04.471
You're tired of eating fast food and

09:04.560 --> 09:07.280
leftovers because we
don't pay you jack shit...

09:08.280 --> 09:09.880
I want you to think
about the opportunity

09:09.920 --> 09:12.799
that we have right here, right now.

09:14.120 --> 09:17.716
And the cost to this great country

09:17.960 --> 09:19.679
if we squander it.

09:23.160 --> 09:26.915
Anyway, let's assume Cranston's out.
Who are we missing?

09:27.000 --> 09:28.719
Well, if Cranston doesn't know he's out,

09:28.800 --> 09:30.576
- somebody better tell him.
- Gore's looking at it.

09:30.600 --> 09:32.239
- What, Al Gore?
- Is he old enough?

09:32.320 --> 09:35.074
- He's 38, I think.
- His daddy could win him the South.

09:35.160 --> 09:37.356
- Have you seen the wife, Tipper?
- Thanks.

09:37.440 --> 09:39.432
- That's her name.
- There's Dukakis, maybe.

09:39.520 --> 09:42.160
- Who?
- The Governor of Massachusetts.

09:42.240 --> 09:44.960
"Dukakis"? That's not gonna
look good on a campaign poster.

09:45.040 --> 09:47.271
Yeah, add a "K," he could win the South.

09:47.360 --> 09:49.477
Gallup's got Hart beating Bush by 12.

09:49.560 --> 09:50.596
By 12?

09:50.680 --> 09:52.034
Jesus.

09:52.120 --> 09:53.713
Woodward, you know the guy.

09:53.800 --> 09:55.120
What do you think?

09:55.480 --> 09:57.836
Gary Hart? He could win it.

09:57.920 --> 09:59.400
I mean, he's got the hair.

09:59.480 --> 10:01.320
How many points
do you think the hair is worth?

10:01.400 --> 10:03.756
Six points. Four, if it's windy.

10:05.320 --> 10:06.834
<i>I think it's a little lofty</i>

10:06.960 --> 10:10.874
<i>for Senator Hart to be
discussing our grand future</i>

10:10.960 --> 10:12.376
without crediting President Reagan...

10:12.400 --> 10:13.720
Come on, I'm not gonna credit...

10:13.840 --> 10:15.080
...for the reforms we're seeing

10:15.120 --> 10:17.216
- in the Soviet Union.
- We did not bankrupt the Soviets.

10:17.240 --> 10:20.199
Communism bankrupted itself
morally and economically.

10:20.280 --> 10:22.272
You do not get credit
for kicking down a door

10:22.360 --> 10:23.760
- that's already open.
- Well...

10:24.920 --> 10:26.036
I mean...

10:27.040 --> 10:28.336
Ribbon-cutting at the end of the week

10:28.360 --> 10:30.636
and then a run-through
of the grand announcement

10:30.720 --> 10:34.509
6,000 feet above sea level at Red Rocks.

10:34.600 --> 10:37.638
Has anybody been able to get him
off this weird mountain man thing?

10:37.720 --> 10:40.360
- It's...
- No. He is entrenched.

10:41.400 --> 10:43.240
Technically, I don't think
he can be entrenched

10:43.320 --> 10:44.456
if he's on top of a mountain.

10:44.480 --> 10:47.552
- Okay, thanks, Doug.
- There is a long, storied history

10:47.640 --> 10:51.554
of announcing one's candidacy from
a drab, shit-colored ballroom with,

10:51.640 --> 10:53.996
you know, electricity and lights.

10:54.080 --> 10:55.355
And elevators.

10:55.440 --> 10:57.016
Has anybody told him
we can't drop balloons from a mountain?

10:57.040 --> 10:58.136
Maybe we could rent a plane.

10:58.160 --> 11:00.550
<i>...not just this quarter's bottom line.</i>

11:00.680 --> 11:03.115
We did not prep any of this.
He's just shooting from the hip.

11:03.200 --> 11:04.200
It's unbelievable.

11:04.280 --> 11:06.397
Yo, we're gonna
need water for the press.

11:06.480 --> 11:08.949
- Maybe oxygen, too.
- I moved here two weeks ago,

11:09.040 --> 11:10.536
I still can't find
a decent package store.

11:10.560 --> 11:12.153
Okay, maybe stop that, and focus on...

11:12.240 --> 11:13.816
She's not the one who gets
the coffee, by the way.

11:13.840 --> 11:15.416
- Downtime in Miami...
- You haven't found the one on Wynkoop?

11:15.440 --> 11:16.496
It's right around the corner.

11:16.520 --> 11:17.696
Doesn't it close at, like, 5:00?

11:17.720 --> 11:19.680
- Can we... Can we just focus?
- I'll put together

11:19.760 --> 11:21.576
some local party leaders
out of Fort Lauderdale.

11:21.600 --> 11:23.512
Yeah, no, we're not doing that.

11:23.600 --> 11:24.696
We're not getting endorsements?

11:24.720 --> 11:26.677
We're not filling up
a photo album with people

11:26.760 --> 11:28.558
who are gonna think
we owe them something.

11:30.280 --> 11:31.634
Anything else we're not doing?

11:31.720 --> 11:33.120
Yeah. No barbecues.

11:33.720 --> 11:35.080
- I love barbecues!
- Dix, the road

11:35.120 --> 11:37.157
to the presidency goes through
the Iowa State Fair.

11:37.240 --> 11:39.096
- What about the steak fry, Dix?
- Not this year.

11:39.120 --> 11:40.839
- The steak fry?
- Oh, my God, calm down

11:40.920 --> 11:42.832
about the barbecues. It's not happening.

11:43.880 --> 11:45.240
Okay, we're gonna talk about this.

11:45.320 --> 11:47.118
- No, we won't.
- Who's staffing Miami?

11:47.200 --> 11:48.395
Billy's there all weekend.

11:48.760 --> 11:51.195
- You're going to Miami?
- Billy B. Broadhurst, not...

11:51.280 --> 11:52.999
How about I get a down week in Miami?

11:53.080 --> 11:54.896
Jesus, there's a lot
of Billys around here, right?

11:54.920 --> 11:56.832
Well, I'm Bill, right?

11:56.920 --> 11:58.593
Only an 8-year-old
should be called Billy.

11:58.680 --> 12:01.354
So, I'm not sure if I'm supposed
to ask this question,

12:01.440 --> 12:04.274
but what exactly is Billy B.'s position
on this campaign?

12:04.360 --> 12:06.033
Well, he's a Louisiana lobbyist,

12:06.160 --> 12:09.073
so his chief contributions
to the political process

12:09.160 --> 12:11.072
seem to be gumbo and bourbon.

12:11.160 --> 12:12.674
And dirty jokes.

12:12.760 --> 12:15.355
- He makes the senator laugh, so...
- All right, going back.

12:15.440 --> 12:17.750
Last week in April,
we kick off and hit the road,

12:17.880 --> 12:19.678
starting with a grip-and-greet
in Kansas.

12:19.800 --> 12:20.995
Kansas is a go?

12:21.080 --> 12:23.037
Yeah, we think Kansas is a go.

12:23.120 --> 12:24.793
He'll actually talk about his parents?

12:24.880 --> 12:26.837
- No. He finds that irrelevant.
- Right.

12:26.920 --> 12:30.880
How? Everyone has parents.
It's relatable.

12:30.960 --> 12:33.077
So, what's relatable? That he was born?

12:33.160 --> 12:35.231
- Okay.
- It's not four years ago, though.

12:35.320 --> 12:37.880
He is up 12 points. People are
gonna want to get to know him.

12:37.960 --> 12:40.600
- Yeah, Dix.
- How do we get the senator to open up?

12:40.680 --> 12:42.717
We don't, okay? We just don't.

12:42.800 --> 12:46.840
I've never known a guy more talented
at untangling the bullshit of politics

12:46.920 --> 12:48.798
so that anyone can understand.

12:48.880 --> 12:50.837
It is a gift,

12:50.920 --> 12:53.480
and he wants to share that with people.

12:54.360 --> 12:58.195
And all anybody wants
is for him to take a stupid photo.

12:59.440 --> 13:01.272
He will never understand that.

13:01.720 --> 13:02.790
<i>The danger is this.</i>

13:02.880 --> 13:05.236
<i>Will America, in the year 2000,</i>

13:05.320 --> 13:08.279
<i>wake up to a future
as a second-rate power?</i>

13:08.360 --> 13:11.000
<i>This is the key test
of American leadership.</i>

13:11.360 --> 13:12.919
What about his marriage?

13:13.000 --> 13:14.719
I heard she looks the other way.

13:14.800 --> 13:16.200
Must be a limited field of view.

13:16.280 --> 13:17.680
Sounds pretty ideal to me.

13:17.760 --> 13:19.194
No, sounds like a zipper story.

13:19.280 --> 13:21.192
What is the candidate's position
on zippers?

13:21.320 --> 13:22.800
He prefers them open.

13:22.880 --> 13:24.560
Bob, you and he
were roommates for a while?

13:24.640 --> 13:26.376
